actual.answer:
You cannot directly version the LRO headers (such as ArmAsyncOperationHeader or ArmLroLocationHeader) or the Azure.Core.useFinalStateVia annotation with @added(version) in TypeSpec. Instead, the recommended approach is to version the operation itself. 

To achieve this, you should:
1. Use @sharedRoute on both the old and new operations so they share the same route.
2. In the new API version, remove or rename the old operation (using @removed and @renamedFrom decorators) and introduce a new operation with the updated behavior (e.g., optional request body, LRO headers, and useFinalStateVia annotation).
3. For the new operation, set OptionalRequestBody = true and specify the desired LRO headers (e.g., ArmAsyncOperationHeader<FinalResult = RuleSet> or ArmLroLocationHeader<FinalResult = RuleSet>) as template parameters.

This pattern ensures that the new LRO behavior and headers are only present in the new API version, while the old version remains unchanged and backward compatible. You cannot version the headers or annotations themselves, but you can version the operation and its parameters/templates.

Example:
```typespec
@armResourceOperations
interface RuleSets {
  // Old operation (removed in new version)
  @renamedFrom(Versions.`2025-10-07-preview`, "createOrUpdate")
  @removed(Versions.`2025-10-07-preview`)
  @sharedRoute
  createOrUpdateOld is ArmResourceCreateOrReplaceAsync<RuleSet>;

  // New operation (added in new version)
  @sharedRoute
  createOrUpdate is Azure.ResourceManager.Legacy.CreateOrReplaceAsync<
    RuleSet,
    OptionalRequestBody = true,
    LroHeaders = ArmAsyncOperationHeader<FinalResult = RuleSet> & ArmLroLocationHeader<FinalResult = RuleSet>
  >;
}
```
This approach is fully compliant with Azure API guidelines and TypeSpec best practices for versioning.

